+0248: cdef class PyDateTime(object):
struct __pyx_obj_6cysgp4_6cysgp4_PyDateTime {
  PyObject_HEAD
  DateTime _cobj;
};


 0249:     '''
 0250:     Thin wrapper around sgp4 (C++) DateTime class.
 0251: 
 0252:     Internally, DateTime objects store time on a linear scale, "ticks",
 0253:     which is the number of micro-seconds since 1. January 0001, 00:00.
 0254:     For convenience, one can convert to and from Python `datetime
 0255:     <https://docs.python.org/3.8/library/datetime.html>`_ objects and
 0256:     `Modified Julian Date (MJD)
 0257:     <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_day#Variants>`_, which is often
 0258:     used in astronomy.
 0259: 
 0260:     For calculating the position of a satellite for a given observer
 0261:     (i.e., in the horizontal frame, Azimuth and Elevation), one needs
 0262:     the `local mean sidereal time
 0263:     <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidereal_time>`_  (derived from Greenwhich
 0264:     mean sidereal time), which can be queried using the
 0265:     `~cysgp4.PyDateTime.lmst()` and `~cysgp4.PyDateTime.gmst()` methods.
 0266: 
 0267:     Parameters
 0268:     ----------
 0269:     dt : `~datetime.datetime` object, or None (default: None)
 0270:         Construct the `~cysgp4.PyDateTime` instance with a given
 0271:         Python `~datetime.datetime` object, or - if None - use the
 0272:         current date and time (as given by `~datetime.datetime.utcnow()`)
 0273:     init : Boolean (default: True)
 0274:         If set to true, the `~datetime.datetime` object will ignore the
 0275:         `dt` parameter and set the internal ticks variable to 0.
 0276:         This is only useful for computationally heavy tasks.
 0277: 
 0278:     Returns
 0279:     -------
 0280:     pydt : `~cysgp4.PyDateTime` object
 0281: 
 0282:     Examples
 0283:     --------
 0284:     There are several possibilities to create a `~cysgp4.PyDateTime` object::
 0285: 
 0286:         >>> from datetime import datetime
 0287:         >>> from cysgp4 import PyDateTime
 0288: 
 0289:         >>> # from Python's datetime
 0290:         >>> dt = datetime(2019, 1, 1, 12, 13, 14)
 0291:         >>> pydt = PyDateTime(dt)
 0292:         >>> pydt
 0293:         <PyDateTime: 2019-01-01 12:13:14.000000 UTC>
 0294: 
 0295:         >>> # from Modified Julian Date
 0296:         >>> mjd = 56458.123
 0297:         >>> pydt = PyDateTime.from_mjd(mjd)
 0298:         >>> pydt
 0299:         <PyDateTime: 2013-06-15 02:57:07.199999 UTC>
 0300: 
 0301:         >>> # from "Ticks"
 0302:         >>> ticks = 58628880000000000  # aka MJD zero point
 0303:         >>> pydt = PyDateTime.from_ticks(ticks)
 0304:         >>> pydt
 0305:         <PyDateTime: 1858-11-17 00:00:00.000000 UTC>
 0306: 
 0307:     Accessing and Modifying the date and time is done via the following
 0308:     properties and methods::
 0309: 
 0310:         >>> print(pydt.datetime)
 0311:         1858-11-17 00:00:00
 0312:         >>> pydt.datetime = datetime(2010, 5, 1, 0, 10, 20)
 0313: 
 0314:         >>> print(pydt.mjd)
 0315:         55317.00717592592
 0316:         >>> pydt.mjd = 55489.01358
 0317: 
 0318:         >>> print(pydt.ticks)
 0319:         63423130773311999
 0320:         >>> pydt.ticks = 63681941594000000
 0321: 
 0322:         >>> observer_longitude = 6.67  # degrees
 0323:         >>> print('GMST: {:9.6f} hours'.format(pydt.gmst()))
 0324:         GMST:  4.959715 hours
 0325:         >>> print('LMST: {:9.6f} hours'.format(pydt.lmst(observer_longitude)))
 0326:         LMST:  5.076129 hours

+0628: cdef class PyTle(object):
struct __pyx_obj_6cysgp4_6cysgp4_PyTle {
  PyObject_HEAD
  Tle *thisptr;
};


 0629:     '''
 0630:     Thin wrapper around sgp4 (C++) Tle class.
 0631: 
 0632:     `Two-line element sets
 0633:     <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-line_element_set>`_ contain the
 0634:     parameters necessary to describe a satellite's orbit (around Earth).
 0635:     Although the name suggests that two lines of strings are used,
 0636:     in practice often three lines are defined, the first containing a
 0637:     satellite name (and/or) ID. It is important to note that for many
 0638:     satellites, the corresponding TLEs get outdated quickly. Especially for
 0639:     low earth orbit satellites, one should query up-to-date information
 0640:     at least once per day.
 0641: 
 0642:     `~cysgp4.PyTle` is only used to parse the TLE strings and store the
 0643:     orbital parameters for use by other sgp4 routines.
 0644: 
 0645:     Parameters
 0646:     ----------
 0647:     name : str
 0648:         Name/ID of satellite.
 0649:     line_one : str
 0650:         First TLE line string.
 0651:     line_two : str
 0652:         Second TLE line string.
 0653: 
 0654:     Returns
 0655:     -------
 0656:     tle : `~cysgp4.PyTle` object
 0657: 
 0658:     Examples
 0659:     --------
 0660:     TLEs can be obtained from many sources, such as
 0661:     `<https://celestrak.com/>`_::
 0662: 
 0663:         >>> import requests
 0664:         >>> from cysgp4 import PyTle
 0665: 
 0666:         >>> url = 'http://celestrak.com/NORAD/elements/science.txt'
 0667:         >>> ctrak_science = requests.get(url)
 0668:         >>> all_lines = ctrak_science.text.split('\\r\\n')
 0669:         >>> tle_list = list(zip(*tuple(
 0670:         ...     all_lines[idx::3]
 0671:         ...     for idx in range(3)
 0672:         ...     )))
 0673:         >>> len(tle_list)
 0674:         >>> print(*tle_list[1], sep='\\n')
 0675:         HST
 0676:         1 20580U 90037B   19321.38711875  .00000471  00000-0  17700-4 0  9991
 0677:         2 20580  28.4699 288.8102 0002495 321.7771 171.5855 15.09299865423838
 0678: 
 0679:         >>> hst_tle = PyTle(*tle_list[1])
 0680:         >>> hst_tle
 0681:         <PyTle: HST                     >
 0682:         >>> print(hst_tle)
 0683:         Norad Number:         20580
 0684:         Int. Designator:      90037B
 0685:         Epoch:                2019-11-17 09:17:27.060000 UTC
 0686:         Orbit Number:         42383
 0687:         Mean Motion Dt2:        0.00000471
 0688:         Mean Motion Ddt6:       0.00000000
 0689:         Eccentricity:           0.00024950
 0690:         BStar:                  0.00001770
 0691:         Inclination:           28.46990000
 0692:         Right Ascending Node: 288.81020000
 0693:         Argument Perigee:     321.77710000
 0694:         Mean Anomaly:         171.58550000
 0695:         Mean Motion:           15.09299865
 0696: 
 0697:     '''
 0698: 
 0699:     # hold the C++ instance, which we're wrapping
 0700:     cdef Tle *thisptr
 0701: 
+0702:     def __init__(self, name, line_one, line_two):

 0994:     '''
 0995:     Thin wrapper around sgp4 (C++) CoordTopocentric struct.
 0996: 
 0997:     The CoordTopocentric struct holds a topocentric location
 0998:     (azimuth, elevation, range/distance and distance/range rate).
 0999: 
 1000:     Note: the topocentric position of a satellite is always relative to
 1001:     an observer (in SGP4 the observer is defined in geographic coordinates).
 1002:     The distance and distance change (aka range rate) is thus the distance
 1003:     between the satellite and the observer. However, this struct/class
 1004:     only holds the azimuth, elevation, distance and distance rate parameters,
 1005:     but contains no information on the observer. It is only useful in
 1006:     conjuction with a `~cysgp4.PyObserver` (which holds a reference to a
 1007:     geographic location) and a datetime; see `~cysgp4.Satellite`.
 1008: 
 1009:     Parameters
 1010:     ----------
 1011:     az_deg : float (default: 0.)
 1012:         Azimuth of topocentric location [deg].
 1013:     el_deg : float (default: 0.)
 1014:         Elevation of topocentric location [deg].
 1015:     dist_km : float (default: 0.)
 1016:         Distance/range of topocentric location [km].
 1017:     dist_rate_km_per_s : float (default: 0.)
 1018:         Distance/range rate of topocentric location [km/s].
 1019: 
 1020:     Returns
 1021:     -------
 1022:     topo : `~cysgp4.PyCoordTopocentric` object
 1023: 
 1024:     Examples
 1025:     --------
 1026:     Constructing and using a `~cysgp4.PyCoordTopocentric` object is
 1027:     straightforward::
 1028: 
 1029:         >>> from cysgp4 import PyCoordTopocentric
 1030: 
 1031:         >>> az_deg, el_deg = 130.1, 10.53
 1032:         >>> dist_km, dist_rate_kms = 1200., 0.03
 1033:         >>> topo = PyCoordTopocentric(az_deg, el_deg, dist_km, dist_rate_kms)
 1034:         >>> topo
 1035:         <PyCoordTopocentric: 130.1000d, 10.5300d, 1200.0000km, 0.0300km/s>
 1036: 
 1037:         >>> # Access is also possible via properties, e.g.:
 1038:         >>> topo.az
 1039:         130.1
 1040:         >>> topo.dist = 1000.
 1041: 
 1042:     '''
 1043: 
 1044:     # hold the C++ instance, which we're wrapping
 1045:     cdef CoordTopocentric _cobj
 1046:

 1123:     '''
 1124:     Thin wrapper around sgp4 (C++) Observer class.
 1125: 
 1126:     The Observer class holds the location (as ECI, see `~cysgp4.PyEci`) of
 1127:     an observer.
 1128: 
 1129:     Note: Usually, a datetime is attached to an ECI location in sgp4.
 1130:     However, the Observer class has no interface to set the datetime
 1131:     and internally it is always set to zero. This is an odd design choice,
 1132:     because a geographic location is not fixed in the ECI system if
 1133:     time passes.
 1134: 
 1135:     Parameters
 1136:     ----------
 1137:     lon_deg : float (default: 0.)
 1138:         Longitude of observer (geographic location) [deg].
 1139:     lat_deg : float (default: 0.)
 1140:         Latitude of observer (geographic location) [deg].
 1141:     alt_km : float (default: 0.)
 1142:         Altitude of observer (geographic location) [km].
 1143: 
 1144:     Returns
 1145:     -------
 1146:     obs : `~cysgp4.PyObserver` object
 1147: 
 1148:     Examples
 1149:     --------
 1150:     Constructing and using a `~cysgp4.PyObserver` object is
 1151:     straightforward::
 1152: 
 1153:         >>> from cysgp4 import PyObserver, PyCoordGeodetic
 1154: 
 1155:         >>> lon_deg, lat_deg = 6.88375, 50.525
 1156:         >>> alt_km = 0.366
 1157:         >>> obs = PyObserver(lon_deg, lat_deg, alt_km)
 1158:         >>> obs
 1159:         <PyObserver: 6.8838d, 50.5250d, 0.3660km>
 1160: 
 1161:         >>> # Access is also possible via location property:
 1162:         >>> obs.loc
 1163:         <PyCoordGeodetic: 6.8838d, 50.5250d, 0.3660km>
 1164:         >>> obs.loc = PyCoordGeodetic(1, 2, 3)
 1165: 
 1166:     '''
 1167: 
 1168:     # hold the C++ instance, which we're wrapping
 1169:     cdef:
 1170:         Observer _cobj
 1171: 
+1172:     def __init__(

+1224: cdef class PyEci(object):
struct __pyx_obj_6cysgp4_6cysgp4_PyEci {
  PyObject_HEAD
  Eci _cobj;

 1225:     '''
 1226:     Thin wrapper around sgp4 (C++) Eci class.
 1227: 
 1228:     The Eci class holds an `ECI location
 1229:     <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth-centered_inertial>`_
 1230:     (latitude, longitude, altitude) for a particular datetime.
 1231: 
 1232:     Note, internally, the coordinates (and velocities) are stored in
 1233:     Cartesian form (read-only!). One can access these, via the
 1234:     `~cysgp4.PyEci.loc` and `~cysgp4.PyEci.vel` properties. Setting
 1235:     new parameters is only possible via a geographic location.
 1236: 
 1237:     Parameters
 1238:     ----------
 1239:     pydt : `~cysgp4.PyDateTime`
 1240:         Date and time.
 1241:     geo_loc : `~cysgp4.PyCoordGeodetic`
 1242:         Geographic location.
 1243: 
 1244:     Returns
 1245:     -------
 1246:     eci : `~cysgp4.PyEci` object
 1247: 
 1248:     Examples
 1249:     --------
 1250:     Constructing and using a `~cysgp4.PyEci` object is
 1251:     straightforward::
 1252: 
 1253:         >>> from cysgp4 import PyEci, PyCoordGeodetic, PyDateTime
 1254: 
 1255:         >>> pydt = PyDateTime.from_mjd(55555.)
 1256:         >>> lon_deg, lat_deg = 6.88375, 50.525
 1257:         >>> alt_km = 0.366
 1258:         >>> geo = PyCoordGeodetic(lon_deg, lat_deg, alt_km)
 1259:         >>> eci = PyEci(pydt, geo)
 1260:         >>> eci
 1261:         <PyEci: 6.8837d, 50.5250d, 0.3660km 2010-12-25 00:00:00.000000 UTC>
 1262: 
 1263:         >>> # Access is also possible via properties, e.g.:
 1264:         >>> eci.loc
 1265:         (-725.3304166274728, 3997.924210010933, 4900.402205553537)
 1266:         >>> eci.pydt = PyDateTime.from_mjd(55556.)
 1267: 
 1268:         >>> # or the update method:
 1269:         >>> eci.update(pydt, PyCoordGeodetic(0, 0, 0))
 1270: 
 1271:     '''
 1272:     cdef:
 1273:         # hold the C++ instance, which we're wrapping
 1274:         Eci _cobj
 1275:

  PyBoolObject *_tle_dirty;

 1365:     '''
 1366:     Calculate position of a satellite at a given time.
 1367: 
 1368:     The satellite is defined via a TLE (see `~cysgp4.PyTle`). Furthermore,
 1369:     for apparent positions of the satellite, an observer (see
 1370:     `~cysgp4.PyObserver`) needs to be defined.
 1371: 
 1372:     The position calculations are lazy, i.e., only calculated if the newly
 1373:     requested time differs by a certain amount from the last time at which
 1374:     a calculation was performed. The granularity of this "cache" can be
 1375:     defined via the `mjd_cache_resolution` parameter.
 1376: 
 1377:     Parameters
 1378:     ----------
 1379:     tle : `~cysgp4.PyTle`
 1380:         TLE instance of the satellite of interest.
 1381:     obs : `~cysgp4.PyObserver` or None (default: None)
 1382:         Observer instance. If `None` then the observer location is set to
 1383:         (0 deg, 0 deg, 0 km).
 1384:     pydt : `~cysgp4.PyDateTime` or `None` (default: None)
 1385:         Date and time at which to calculate the position. If `None` then
 1386:         the current datetime is used, as given by a call to
 1387:         `~datetime.datetime.utcnow()`.
 1388:     mjd_cache_resolution : double (default: 0.001)
 1389:         Granularity of the internal cache [s]. Satellite positions are
 1390:         calculated only if the newly requested datetime differs by more than
 1391:         this from the previous calculation.
 1392:     on_error : str, optional (either 'raise' or 'coerce_to_nan', default: 'raise')
 1393:         If the underlying SGP C++ library throws an error (which often
 1394:         happens if one works with times that are strongly deviating from
 1395:         the TLE epoch), a Python RuntimeError is usually thrown. For batch
 1396:         processing, this is not always desirable. If
 1397:         `on_error = 'coerce_to_nan'` then C++ errors will be suppressed and
 1398:         the resulting position vectors will be converted to NaN-values
 1399:         instead.
 1400: 
 1401:     Returns
 1402:     -------
 1403:     sat : `~cysgp4.Satellite` object
 1404: 
 1405:     Examples
 1406:     --------
 1407:     The following demonstrates how a typical use of the `~cysgp4.Satellite`
 1408:     class would look like::
 1409: 
 1410:         >>> from cysgp4 import *
 1411: 
 1412:         >>> pydt = PyDateTime.from_mjd(58805.57)
 1413:         >>> lon_deg, lat_deg = 6.88375, 50.525
 1414:         >>> alt_km = 0.366
 1415:         >>> obs = PyObserver(lon_deg, lat_deg, alt_km)
 1416: 
 1417:         >>> hst_tle = PyTle(
 1418:         ... 'HST',
 1419:         ... '1 20580U 90037B   19321.38711875  .00000471  00000-0  17700-4 0  9991',
 1420:         ... '2 20580  28.4699 288.8102 0002495 321.7771 171.5855 15.09299865423838',
 1421:         ... )
 1422: 
 1423:         >>> sat = Satellite(hst_tle, obs, pydt)
 1424:         >>> # can now query positions, also for different times
 1425:         >>> sat.eci_pos().loc  # ECI cartesian position
 1426:         (5879.5931344459295, 1545.7455647032068, 3287.4155452595)
 1427:         >>> sat.eci_pos().vel  # ECI cartesian velocity
 1428:         (-1.8205895517672226, 7.374044252723081, -0.20697960810978586)
 1429:         >>> sat.geo_pos()  # geographic position
 1430:         <PyCoordGeodetic: 112.2146d, 28.5509d, 538.0186km>
 1431:         >>> sat.topo_pos()  # topocentric position
 1432:         <PyCoordTopocentric: 60.2453d, -35.6844d, 8314.5683km, 3.5087km/s>
 1433: 
 1434:         >>> # change time
 1435:         >>> sat.mjd += 1 / 720.  # one minute later
 1436:         >>> sat.topo_pos()
 1437:         <PyCoordTopocentric: 54.8446d, -38.2749d, 8734.9195km, 3.4885km/s>
 1438: 
 1439:         >>> # change by less than cache resolution (1 ms)
 1440:         >>> sat.topo_pos().az, sat.topo_pos().el
 1441:         (54.84463503781068, -38.274852915850126)
 1442:         >>> sat.mjd += 0.0005 / 86400.  # 0.5 ms
 1443:         >>> sat.topo_pos().az, sat.topo_pos().el
 1444:         (54.84463503781068, -38.274852915850126)
 1445:         >>> # change by another 0.5 ms triggers re-calculation
 1446:         >>> sat.mjd += 0.00051 / 86400.
 1447:         >>> sat.topo_pos().az, sat.topo_pos().el
 1448:         (54.844568313870965, -38.274885794151324)
 1449: 
 1450:     '''
 1451:

+1647: def _propagate_many_cysgp4(
/* Python wrapper */
static PyObject *__pyx_pw_6cysgp4_6cysgp4_3_propagate_many_cysgp4(PyObject *__pyx_self, 
#if CYTHON_METH_FASTCALL
PyObject *const *__pyx_args, Py_ssize_t __pyx_nargs, PyObject *__pyx_kwds
#else
PyObject *__pyx_args, PyObject *__pyx_kwds
#endif
); /*proto*/
PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6cysgp4_6cysgp4_2_propagate_many_cysgp4, "_propagate_many_cysgp4(mjds, tles, observers=None, bool do_eci_pos=True, bool do_eci_vel=True, bool do_geo=True, bool do_topo=True, bool do_obs_pos=False, bool do_sat_azel=False, unicode sat_frame=u'zxy', unicode on_error=u'raise')\n\n    Calculate positions of many satellites at a various times at once.\n\n    This is an array interface to the sgp4 calculations, which allows to\n    perform calculations for different satellite TLEs, observers and times\n    in a parallelized manner. `~numpy` broadcasting rules apply.\n\n    With the Boolean parameters, `do_eci_pos`, `do_eci_vel`, `do_geo`,\n    `do_topo`, `do_obs_pos`, and `do_sat_azel` the user can decide, which\n    position frames are returned in the output dictionary.\n\n    Satellite are defined via TLEs (see `~cysgp4.PyTle`). The\n    `~.cysgp4.propagate_many` function works with a single (scalar) PyTle\n    object or a list/array of them. The same is true for the `mjds` and\n    optional `observers` parameters, which must be a scalar (a double and\n    `~cysgp4.PyObserver` instance, respectively) or a list/array of them.\n\n    As in most use cases, a large number of positions is probably queried,\n    the returned values do not use the `~cysgp4.PyEci` or\n    `~cysgp4.PyCoordTopocentric` classes, but pack everything in arrays.\n    This is not only faster, but makes it easier to further process the\n    results.\n\n    For parallelization, `OpenMP <https://www.openmp.org/>`_ is utilized.\n    To change the number of CPU cores that are used, one can either set\n    the environment variable `OMP_NUM_THREADS` or use\n    `~cysgp4.set_num_threads`.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    mjds : `~numpy.ndarray`, `~list`, or scalar of float\n        Modified Julian Date.\n    tles : `~numpy.ndarray`, `~list`, or scalar of `~cysgp4.PyTle`\n        TLE instance of the satellite of interest.\n    observers : `~numpy.ndarray`, `~list`, or scalar of `~cysgp4.PyObserver` or None (default: None)\n        Observer instan""ce. If `None` then the observer location is set to\n        (0 deg, 0 deg, 0 km).\n    do_eci_pos : Boolean, optional (default: True)\n        Whether to include ECI cartesian positions in the result.\n    do_eci_vel : Boolean, optional (default: True)\n        Whether to include ECI cartesian velocity in the result.\n    do_geo : Boolean, optional (default: True)\n        Whether to include geographic/geodetic positions in the result.\n    do_topo : Boolean, optional (default: True)\n        Whether to include topocentric positions in the result.\n    do_obs_pos : Boolean, optional (default: True)\n        Whether to include the observer ECI position in the results.\n    do_sat_azel : Boolean, optional (default: True)\n        Whether to include the observer position as seen by the satellite\n        (distance/azimuth/elevation) in the results.\n    sat_frame : 'zxy' or 'xyz', optional (default: 'zxy')\n        How the moving satellite frame is defined. Two options are\n        implemented, 'zxy' and 'xyz'.  If 'zxy' is chosen, the moving\n        satellite frame is constructed such that the `z` axis is aligned with\n        the satellite motion vector. The `y` axis is constructed as a vector\n        that is perpendicular to the plane defined by the motion vector and\n        the ECI zero point (aka Earth center). The resulting `x` axis, which\n        is orthogonal to the `y` and `z` axes, is then approximately pointing\n        to the nadir. Alternatively, if the frame is set as `xyz`, the `x`\n        axes is the motion vector, `y` has the same meaning and `z` is\n        approximately pointing towards the nadir.\n    on_error : str, optional (either 'raise' or 'coerce_to_nan', default: 'raise')\n        If the underlying SGP C++ library throws an error (which often\n        happens if one works with times that are strongly deviating from\n        the TLE epoch), a Python RuntimeError is usually thrown. For batch\n        processing, this is not always desirabl""e. If\n        `on_error = 'coerce_to_nan'` then C++ errors will be suppressed and\n        the resulting position vectors will be converted to NaN-values\n        instead.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    result : dict\n        Resulting positions for each requested frame:\n\n        - `eci_pos` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float\n\n          Satellites ECI cartesian positions. Last dimension has length 3,\n          one for each of `x`, `y`, and `z`.\n\n        - `eci_vel` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float\n\n          Satellites ECI cartesian velicities. Last dimension has length 3,\n          one for each of `v_x`, `v_y`, and `v_z`.\n\n        - `geo` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float\n\n          Satellites Geodetic positions. Last dimension has length 3, one\n          for each of `lon`, `lat`, and `alt`.\n\n        - `topo` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float\n\n          Satellites Topocentric positions. Last dimension has length 4,\n          one for each of `az`, `el`, `dist`, and `dist_rate`.\n\n        - `obs_pos` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float\n\n          Observer positions in ECI frame (Cartesian). Last dimension has\n          length 3, one for each of `x`, `y`, and `z`.\n\n        - `sat_azel` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float\n\n          Observer positions in the (moving) satellite frame either given as\n          azimuth (aka across track), elevation (aka along track), and\n          distance - if `sat_frame` is 'zxy', or given as 'theta', 'phi', and\n          distance if `sat_frame` is 'xyz' (with ISO definition of the angles\n          theta and phi); see also `sat_frame` parameter description. Last\n          dimension has length 3, one for each of, (`az`, `el`, `dist`) or\n          (`theta', `phi`, `dist`), respectively.\n\n        In all cases the first dimensions are determined by the\n        (broadcasted) shape of the inputs `mjd`, `tles`, and `observers`.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    The following demonstrates how to use the `~cysgp4.propagate_many`\n    function::""\n\n        >>> import numpy as np\n        >>> from cysgp4 import PyTle, PyObserver, propagate_many\n        >>> from cysgp4 import get_example_tles, tles_from_text\n\n        >>> tle_text = get_example_tles()\n        >>> tles = np.array(\n        ...     tles_from_text(tle_text)\n        ...     )[np.newaxis, np.newaxis, :20]  # use first 20 TLEs\n        >>> observers = np.array([\n        ...     PyObserver(6.88375, 50.525, 0.366),\n        ...     PyObserver(16.88375, 50.525, 0.366),\n        ...     ])[np.newaxis, :, np.newaxis]\n        >>> mjds = np.linspace(\n        ...     58805.5, 58806.5, 1000  # 1000 time steps\n        ...     )[:, np.newaxis, np.newaxis]\n\n        >>> result = propagate_many(mjds, tles, observers)\n        >>> print(sorted(result.keys()))\n        ['eci_pos', 'eci_vel', 'geo', 'topo']\n\n        >>> # shapes are as follows\n        >>> print(np.broadcast(mjds, tles, observers).shape)\n        (1000, 2, 20)\n        >>> print(result['eci_pos'].shape, result['topo'].shape)\n        (1000, 2, 20, 3) (1000, 2, 20, 4)\n\n        >>> result = propagate_many(\n        ...     mjds, tles, observers,\n        ...     do_eci_pos=False, do_eci_vel=False, do_geo=False, do_topo=True\n        ...     )\n        >>> print(sorted(result.keys()))\n        ['topo']\n\n    ");

 1652:         str sat_frame='zxy', str on_error='raise',
 1653:         ):
 1654:     '''
 1655:     Calculate positions of many satellites at a various times at once.
 1656: 
 1657:     This is an array interface to the sgp4 calculations, which allows to
 1658:     perform calculations for different satellite TLEs, observers and times
 1659:     in a parallelized manner. `~numpy` broadcasting rules apply.
 1660: 
 1661:     With the Boolean parameters, `do_eci_pos`, `do_eci_vel`, `do_geo`,
 1662:     `do_topo`, `do_obs_pos`, and `do_sat_azel` the user can decide, which
 1663:     position frames are returned in the output dictionary.
 1664: 
 1665:     Satellite are defined via TLEs (see `~cysgp4.PyTle`). The
 1666:     `~.cysgp4.propagate_many` function works with a single (scalar) PyTle
 1667:     object or a list/array of them. The same is true for the `mjds` and
 1668:     optional `observers` parameters, which must be a scalar (a double and
 1669:     `~cysgp4.PyObserver` instance, respectively) or a list/array of them.
 1670: 
 1671:     As in most use cases, a large number of positions is probably queried,
 1672:     the returned values do not use the `~cysgp4.PyEci` or
 1673:     `~cysgp4.PyCoordTopocentric` classes, but pack everything in arrays.
 1674:     This is not only faster, but makes it easier to further process the
 1675:     results.
 1676: 
 1677:     For parallelization, `OpenMP <https://www.openmp.org/>`_ is utilized.
 1678:     To change the number of CPU cores that are used, one can either set
 1679:     the environment variable `OMP_NUM_THREADS` or use
 1680:     `~cysgp4.set_num_threads`.
 1681: 
 1682:     Parameters
 1683:     ----------
 1684:     mjds : `~numpy.ndarray`, `~list`, or scalar of float
 1685:         Modified Julian Date.
 1686:     tles : `~numpy.ndarray`, `~list`, or scalar of `~cysgp4.PyTle`
 1687:         TLE instance of the satellite of interest.
 1688:     observers : `~numpy.ndarray`, `~list`, or scalar of `~cysgp4.PyObserver` or None (default: None)
 1689:         Observer instance. If `None` then the observer location is set to
 1690:         (0 deg, 0 deg, 0 km).
 1691:     do_eci_pos : Boolean, optional (default: True)
 1692:         Whether to include ECI cartesian positions in the result.
 1693:     do_eci_vel : Boolean, optional (default: True)
 1694:         Whether to include ECI cartesian velocity in the result.
 1695:     do_geo : Boolean, optional (default: True)
 1696:         Whether to include geographic/geodetic positions in the result.
 1697:     do_topo : Boolean, optional (default: True)
 1698:         Whether to include topocentric positions in the result.
 1699:     do_obs_pos : Boolean, optional (default: True)
 1700:         Whether to include the observer ECI position in the results.
 1701:     do_sat_azel : Boolean, optional (default: True)
 1702:         Whether to include the observer position as seen by the satellite
 1703:         (distance/azimuth/elevation) in the results.
 1704:     sat_frame : 'zxy' or 'xyz', optional (default: 'zxy')
 1705:         How the moving satellite frame is defined. Two options are
 1706:         implemented, 'zxy' and 'xyz'.  If 'zxy' is chosen, the moving
 1707:         satellite frame is constructed such that the `z` axis is aligned with
 1708:         the satellite motion vector. The `y` axis is constructed as a vector
 1709:         that is perpendicular to the plane defined by the motion vector and
 1710:         the ECI zero point (aka Earth center). The resulting `x` axis, which
 1711:         is orthogonal to the `y` and `z` axes, is then approximately pointing
 1712:         to the nadir. Alternatively, if the frame is set as `xyz`, the `x`
 1713:         axes is the motion vector, `y` has the same meaning and `z` is
 1714:         approximately pointing towards the nadir.
 1715:     on_error : str, optional (either 'raise' or 'coerce_to_nan', default: 'raise')
 1716:         If the underlying SGP C++ library throws an error (which often
 1717:         happens if one works with times that are strongly deviating from
 1718:         the TLE epoch), a Python RuntimeError is usually thrown. For batch
 1719:         processing, this is not always desirable. If
 1720:         `on_error = 'coerce_to_nan'` then C++ errors will be suppressed and
 1721:         the resulting position vectors will be converted to NaN-values
 1722:         instead.
 1723: 
 1724:     Returns
 1725:     -------
 1726:     result : dict
 1727:         Resulting positions for each requested frame:
 1728: 
 1729:         - `eci_pos` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float
 1730: 
 1731:           Satellites ECI cartesian positions. Last dimension has length 3,
 1732:           one for each of `x`, `y`, and `z`.
 1733: 
 1734:         - `eci_vel` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float
 1735: 
 1736:           Satellites ECI cartesian velicities. Last dimension has length 3,
 1737:           one for each of `v_x`, `v_y`, and `v_z`.
 1738: 
 1739:         - `geo` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float
 1740: 
 1741:           Satellites Geodetic positions. Last dimension has length 3, one
 1742:           for each of `lon`, `lat`, and `alt`.
 1743: 
 1744:         - `topo` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float
 1745: 
 1746:           Satellites Topocentric positions. Last dimension has length 4,
 1747:           one for each of `az`, `el`, `dist`, and `dist_rate`.
 1748: 
 1749:         - `obs_pos` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float
 1750: 
 1751:           Observer positions in ECI frame (Cartesian). Last dimension has
 1752:           length 3, one for each of `x`, `y`, and `z`.
 1753: 
 1754:         - `sat_azel` : `~numpy.ndarray` of float
 1755: 
 1756:           Observer positions in the (moving) satellite frame either given as
 1757:           azimuth (aka across track), elevation (aka along track), and
 1758:           distance - if `sat_frame` is 'zxy', or given as 'theta', 'phi', and
 1759:           distance if `sat_frame` is 'xyz' (with ISO definition of the angles
 1760:           theta and phi); see also `sat_frame` parameter description. Last
 1761:           dimension has length 3, one for each of, (`az`, `el`, `dist`) or
 1762:           (`theta', `phi`, `dist`), respectively.
 1763: 
 1764:         In all cases the first dimensions are determined by the
 1765:         (broadcasted) shape of the inputs `mjd`, `tles`, and `observers`.
 1766: 
 1767:     Examples
 1768:     --------
 1769:     The following demonstrates how to use the `~cysgp4.propagate_many`
 1770:     function::
 1771: 
 1772:         >>> import numpy as np
 1773:         >>> from cysgp4 import PyTle, PyObserver, propagate_many
 1774:         >>> from cysgp4 import get_example_tles, tles_from_text
 1775: 
 1776:         >>> tle_text = get_example_tles()
 1777:         >>> tles = np.array(
 1778:         ...     tles_from_text(tle_text)
 1779:         ...     )[np.newaxis, np.newaxis, :20]  # use first 20 TLEs
 1780:         >>> observers = np.array([
 1781:         ...     PyObserver(6.88375, 50.525, 0.366),
 1782:         ...     PyObserver(16.88375, 50.525, 0.366),
 1783:         ...     ])[np.newaxis, :, np.newaxis]
 1784:         >>> mjds = np.linspace(
 1785:         ...     58805.5, 58806.5, 1000  # 1000 time steps
 1786:         ...     )[:, np.newaxis, np.newaxis]
 1787: 
 1788:         >>> result = propagate_many(mjds, tles, observers)
 1789:         >>> print(sorted(result.keys()))
 1790:         ['eci_pos', 'eci_vel', 'geo', 'topo']
 1791: 
 1792:         >>> # shapes are as follows
 1793:         >>> print(np.broadcast(mjds, tles, observers).shape)
 1794:         (1000, 2, 20)
 1795:         >>> print(result['eci_pos'].shape, result['topo'].shape)
 1796:         (1000, 2, 20, 3) (1000, 2, 20, 4)
 1797: 
 1798:         >>> result = propagate_many(
 1799:         ...     mjds, tles, observers,
 1800:         ...     do_eci_pos=False, do_eci_vel=False, do_geo=False, do_topo=True
 1801:         ...     )
 1802:         >>> print(sorted(result.keys()))
 1803:         ['topo']
 1804: 
 1805:     '''
